.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf - custom implementation of the C library printf function

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a
.I format
string. It writes characters to the standard output stream
.B stdout
using the write(2) system call.

The format string contains ordinary characters, which are printed as-is,
and conversion specifiers starting with '%'.

This implementation handles the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.
If the argument is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.

.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer (same as %d).

.PP
Unsupported specifiers are printed literally: the '%' followed by the unknown character.

.PP
This simplified version does not support the standard printf features:
flags, field width, precision, length modifiers, or buffering.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.B _printf
function returns the number of characters printed
(excluding the terminating null byte).
If an error occurs, such as a NULL format string, the function returns
.B -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print a character:
.PP
.EX
_printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');
.EE

Print a string:
.PP
.EX
_printf("String: %s\n", "Holberton");
.EE

Print integers:
.PP
.EX
_printf("Value: %d\n", 1024);
_printf("Value: %i\n", -42);
.EE

Print a percent sign:
.PP
.EX
_printf("Percent: %%\n");
.EE

.SH DATE
November 2025

